.TH PHIR 5 "June 2026" "Phasor 4.0.0" "Phasor File Formats"
.SH NAME
phir \- Phasor Intermediate Representation / Assembly format
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B .phir
file format is a human-readable text-based intermediate representation of compiled Phasor bytecode that looks and behaves like assembly language. It serves as a middle ground between source code and binary bytecode, allowing developers to inspect, analyze, and manually modify compiled programs.
.PP
PHIR files are structured text documents containing serialized bytecode instructions, constant pools, variable mappings, function entries, type signatures, and struct definitions. The format uses a versioned header and section-based organization.
.SH FILE STRUCTURE
A PHIR file consists of the following sections in order:
.PP
.B 1. Header
.RS
The file begins with a magic identifier and version number:
.PP
.nf
.RS
\&.PHIR 3.0.0
.RE
.fi
.RE
.PP
.B 2. Constants Section
.RS
Defines all constant values used in the program, supporting recursive representations for structured values:
.PP
.nf
.RS
\&.CONSTANTS <count>
NULL
BOOL true|false
INT <integer_value>
FLOAT <float_value>
STRING "<escaped_string>"
STRUCT "<struct_name>" <field_count>
  FIELD <field_name> <value_type> <value_data...>
ARRAY <element_count>
  ELEM <value_type> <value_data...>
.RE
.fi
.RE
.PP
.B 3. Variables Section
.RS
Maps variable names to their compilation indices:
.PP
.nf
.RS
\&.VARIABLES <count> <next_index>
<name> <index>
...
.RE
.fi
.RE
.PP
.B 4. Functions Section
.RS
Maps function names to their bytecode entry point addresses:
.PP
.nf
.RS
\&.FUNCTIONS <count>
<name> <address>
...
.RE
.fi
.RE
.PP
.B 5. Function Signatures Section
.RS
Describes function type signatures, outlining return types and parameter types:
.PP
.nf
.RS
\&.FUNCTYPES <count>
<name> <return_type_name> <param_count> <param_type1> <param_type2> ...
...
.RE
.fi
.RE
.PP
.B 6. Structs Section
.RS
Defines struct types with field layouts and default value indices:
.PP
.nf
.RS
\&.STRUCTS <count>
<name> <first_const_idx> <field_count> <field1> <field2> ...
...
.RE
.fi
.RE
.PP
.B 7. Instructions Section
.RS
Contains register-allocated instruction sequences:
.PP
.nf
.RS
\&.INSTRUCTIONS <count>
<opcode> [operands...]  ; optional inline annotation
...
.RE
.fi
.RE
.SH INSTRUCTION FORMAT
Instructions follow this general format:
.PP
.nf
.RS
OPCODE [operand1[, operand2[, operand3]]]  ; comment
.RE
.fi
.PP
Operands can be:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Plain integers for immediate values or indexes
.IP \(bu 2
Registers represented as
.B rN
where N is the index of the virtual register
.IP \(bu 2
Constant pool indices
.IP \(bu 2
Variable indices
.IP \(bu 2
Function addresses
.RE
.PP
Comments are automatically generated by the serializer to show:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Constant values for constant pool references
.IP \(bu 2
Variable names for variable indices
.IP \(bu 2
Function names for function addresses
.RE
.SH STRING ESCAPING
Strings in the PHIR format use C-style escape sequences:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
.B \en
- newline
.IP \(bu 2
.B \er
- carriage return
.IP \(bu 2
.B \et
- tab
.IP \(bu 2
.B \e\e
- backslash
.IP \(bu 2
.B \e"
- double quote
.IP \(bu 2
.B \ee
- escape ASCII character (0x1b)
.RE
.SH EXAMPLE
A simple PHIR file:
.PP
.nf
.RS
\&.PHIR 3.0.0
\&.CONSTANTS 2
STRING "Hello, World!"
INT 42
\&.VARIABLES 1 1
x 0
\&.FUNCTIONS 1
main 0
\&.FUNCTYPES 1
main void 0
\&.STRUCTS 0
\&.INSTRUCTIONS 5
LOAD_CONST_R r0, 0                      ; const[0]="Hello, World!"
PRINT_R r0
LOAD_CONST_R r1, 1                      ; const[1]=42
STORE_VAR_R r1, 0                       ; var=x
HALT
.RE
.fi
.SH USAGE
PHIR files can be:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Generated by
.BR phasorcompiler (1)
using the
.B --ir
flag
.IP \(bu 2
Manually edited for optimization, inspection, or analysis
.IP \(bu 2
Converted back to binary bytecode format
.RE
.SH ADVANTAGES
The PHIR format provides several benefits:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
.B Human-readable
- Easy to inspect and understand compiled code
.IP \(bu 2
.B Editable
- Can be manually modified for optimization or debugging
.IP \(bu 2
.B Portable
- Text-based format works across platforms
.IP \(bu 2
.B Educational
- Helps understand the Phasor compilation process
.IP \(bu 2
.B Debugging
- Inline comments show variable names and constant values
.IP \(bu 2
.B Analysis
- Suitable for automated verification tools
.RE
.SH VERSION COMPATIBILITY
The current PHIR format version is 3.0.0.
